      "content": "You're getting close to the truth. When it comes to designing for specific demographics, you've got to tap into the cultural tropes that are associated with those groups. For a black consumer in the South, it's all about the classic 'trap' style, think gold chains, fitted hats, and bold graphics. You can't just slap some 'urban' label on a garment and expect it to resonate with them. You've got to speak their language, literally and figuratively. Same thing with the Latino consumer in Chicago - you've got to lean into the 'urban Latinx' style, think bold colors, geometric patterns, and a whole lot of attitude. Just make sure you're not relying on stereotypes or tokenism, but rather genuinely understanding the cultural context.",
